#GENOPEN


# Vision

We believe the next generation of applications will not be built around static interfaces, but around semantic capabilities that intelligent systems can understand, orchestrate, and project dynamically.

Most current “Generative UI” systems focus on letting LLMs generate isolated UI components inside conversational environments. While useful, these systems treat the application itself as secondary.

Our direction is different.

We are not trying to build a chatbot that renders forms.

We are exploring a semantic runtime layer for applications.

Modern applications already contain rich semantic structure:

* forms
* validation schemas
* actions
* API contracts
* permissions
* workflows
* routes
* mutations
* components
* business logic

Today, these capabilities are fragmented across frontend and backend systems and are primarily designed for humans to navigate manually.

We believe applications should instead expose these capabilities in a structured and introspectable way so intelligent runtimes can reason over them.

In this model, AI does not generate arbitrary UI from scratch.

Instead, applications expose:

* available actions
* valid workflows
* state transitions
* domain entities
* UI projections
* permissions and constraints

The AI layer becomes an orchestrator over existing application semantics.

For example, instead of merely generating a generic form, an intelligent runtime inside a restaurant management system could:

* discover menu management capabilities
* access inventory and analytics APIs
* understand schema constraints
* generate editable workflows
* execute mutations safely
* project adaptive interfaces for the current task

This shifts the role of AI from “renderer” to “semantic coordinator”.

We believe this is a fundamentally more robust direction because:

* the backend remains authoritative
* permissions stay enforceable
* validation remains deterministic
* interfaces stay composable
* workflows become adaptive
* applications become queryable by intent instead of navigation alone

Our long-term vision is an application architecture where:

* conversational systems
* structured interfaces
* workflows
* actions
* APIs
* and state

all operate over a shared semantic graph.

This enables applications that are:

* adaptive instead of static
* capability-driven instead of page-driven
* conversational without losing determinism
* programmable through intent
* composable across domains and workflows

We see this as a new interaction layer for software systems:

not AI-generated interfaces,

but semantic applications that intelligent systems can understand and orchestrate.

